04580nam a22006735i 9780691188430DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182003nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911884307 a10.1515/97806911884302doi  a(DE-B1597)501655  a(OCoLC)1076416316  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDR2214b.B76 2003eb 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a949.76/012231 aBrown, Keith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Past in Question :bModern Macedonia and the Uncertainties of Nation /cKeith Brown. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tPreface -- tNotes on Transliteration and Pronunciation -- tCHAPTER ONE. Introduction -- tCHAPTER TWO. A Double Legacy -- tCHAPTER THREE. "Crowded Out by a Plethora of Facts" -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Tipping Points -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Between the Revolutions -- tCHAPTER SIX. Buying the Memories -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. History Stated -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Local Truths -- tCHAPTER NINE. On the Brink of a New, Old World -- tCHAPTER TEN. Conclusion -- tGlossary and Acronyms -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book examines the relationship between national history, identity, and politics in twentieth-century Macedonia. It focuses on the reverberating power of events surrounding an armed uprising in August 1903, when a revolutionary organization challenged the forces of the Ottoman Empire by seizing control of the mountain town of Krusevo. A century later, Krusevo is part of the Republic of Macedonia and a site for yearly commemorations of 1903. In the course of the intervening hundred years, various communities have vied to establish an authoritative account of what happened in 1903--and to weave those events into a longer and wider narrative of social, cultural, and national evolution. Keith Brown examines how Krusevo's residents, refugees, and exiles have participated--along with scholars, journalists, artists, bureaucrats, and politicians--in a conversation about their vexed past. By tracing different approaches to understanding, commemorating, and narrating the events of 1903, he shows how in this small mountain town the "magic of nationalism" by which destiny is written into particular historical events has neither failed nor wholly succeeded. Stories of heroism, self-sacrifice, and unity still rub against tales of treachery, score settling, and disaster as people come to terms with the legacies of imperialism, socialism, and nationalism. The efforts of Krusevo's successive generations to transcend a past of intercommunal violence reveal how rival claims to knowledge and truth acquire vital significance during rapid social, economic, and political change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNationalismzMacedoniaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691188430zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691188430423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691188430.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK